x4freetext: 20-GeV proton synchro-cyclotron,
n-TOF facility, CERN. Pulsed proton beam of high
intensity of 7.E+12 protons per bunch, pulse width
6 nanosec, repetition rate of 0.4 to 0.8 Hz
Spallation reaction of fast protons on the
massive lead target moderated in a surrounding
5.8 cm thick water cooling layer surrounding the
target.The moderation process produces a nearly 1/E
isolethargic flux up to 1 MeV. Background owing to
fast-charged particles is suppressed by a 1.5-T
sweeping magnet, heavy concrete walls, and 3.5-m-thick
iron shielding.
The high instantaneous neutron flux (10**5
neutrons/cm2/pulse at the measuring position), high
resolution (3*10**-4 at 1 eV, 1.5*10**-3 at 30 keV),
and low background.
Relative neutron flux was measured with a low-mass
flux monitor of Mylar foil 1.5 microm thick with layer
of 200 microg/cm**2 Li-6. Charged particles emitted in
Li-6(n,alpha)H-3 reactions were detected by a set of
four Si detectors surrounding the Li-6 sample outside
the neutron beam. The monitor sample was located 1.5 m
upstream of the capture samples. The neutron beam was
also periodically checked by calibration runs with gold
reference samples.
Flight path 185.2 m with collimators at 135
and 175 m from the target.
Pulse height weighting technique to determine
absolute capture yields.
Two C6-D6 liquid scin. cells as gamma detectors
placed perpendicular to neutron beam at a distance of
3 cm from beam axis. Background owing to in-beam
gamma-rays from (n,gamma) reactions in water moderator
was reduced by placing the detectors 9.2 cm upstream of
the sample position.
Detectors were calibrated in regular intervals by
Cs-137 (662-keV), Co-60 (1173- and 1332-keV) sources.
Additional calibration point at 6.13 MeV was obtained
with a composite Pu-238/C-13 source.
Two liquid scintillator detectors cover a restricted
solid angle far below 4PI, resulting in an overall
efficiency for the detection of capture events of 20%.
U-235 loaded parallel-plate fission
chamber from PTB Braunschweig - for neutron flux
measurement as well as Li-6 neutron flux monitors.
Li-6 glass detector and four silicon
detectors - for relative neutron flux monitoring .
For neutron flux
measurement
The normalization to a reference cross section was
performed by means of the saturated resonance technique
using the prominent 4.9-eV resonance in Au-197.
Zr-O2 oxide powder pressed to pellet of 22 mm diameter,
thickness 0.07 cm, mass 1.349 g, encapsulated in
0.2-mm-thick aluminum can. Isotope composition:
Traces of Hf, Sn, Na,Mg, and Al were also present in
the sample. The contribution of these impurities to
the measured capture yield was not negligible.
Monitors: Metallic gold sample, 22 mm diameter,
thickness 0.001498 atoms/barn - for neutron flux
measurements.
Lead metallic sample, 22 mm diameter, thickness
0.0029916 atoms/barn - for background measurements.
Metal of natural composition.
Also additional carbon  sample of the same diameter
Experimental capture yield was determined by the
weighted net count rate, the effective binding energy,
the integrated neutron flux, the overall background.
The weighted net count rate was normalized to the
effective binding energy and to the integrated neutron
flux.
For backgrounds:
-contribution of scattered neutrons to the background
was evaluated by means of a carbon sample and was found
to be negligible in the spectra of 92Zr;
-Measurements with an empty Al can showed that only
a few well-known Al resonances were identifiable in
the Zr spectra; this very small background component
was easily subtracted;
-in-beam gamma-rays contribution (about 70% of total
background) was studied with a lead sample;
-The correction for comparably low ambient background
was negligible.
M.M.

x4freetext: Resonance energy.
Gamma-width G-gamma.
Neutron width G-n.
Capture kernel.
Experimental capture yield has been analyzed in the
Reich-Moore approximation with the multilevel R-matrix
program SAMMY. The analysis was limited to the energy
range between 2 and 40 keV.
Gn was kept fixed in the fit to the values reported in
the literature for all resonances except the first one,
for which G-gamma was fixed instead.
Spin factors were fixed to the values reported in the
evaluated library JENDL-3.3.
Statistical spin factor g was determined by resonance
spin J, the spin of the incident neutron In = 1/2, and
the spin of the target nucleus IZr = 0.
For the resonances observed in this work for the first
time, only the capture kernel is reported.
